The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` is the modern web component replacement for the legacy `Autocomplete` widget. You append it to the DOM, then listen for the `gmp-placeselect` event, which fires when a user selects a suggestion. After selection, you call `fetchFields()` on the returned `Place` object to retrieve the specific data you need [Source 1].

Here's a complete working example:

```javascript
async function initAutocomplete() {
  // Load the places library
  const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");
  const { Map } = await google.maps.importLibrary("maps");
  const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("marker");

  // Initialize your map
  const map = new Map(document.getElementById("map"), {
    center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
    zoom: 12,
    mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID",
  });

  // Create and configure the autocomplete element
  const placeAutocomplete = new PlaceAutocompleteElement({
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" }, // Optional: restrict to a country
  });

  // Attach it to your search container in the DOM
  document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

  // Listen for place selection
  placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
    const place = event.place;

    // Fetch only the fields you need (field masking controls billing)
    await place.fetchFields({
      fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"],
    });

    // Use the place data
    console.log("Name:", place.displayName);
    console.log("Address:", place.formattedAddress);

    // Pan the map to the selected location
    if (place.location) {
      map.setCenter(place.location);
      map.setZoom(15);

      // Drop a marker at the selected place
      new AdvancedMarkerElement({
        map,
        position: place.location,
        title: place.displayName,
      });
    }
  });
}

initAutocomplete();
```

```html
<!-- Required HTML structure -->
<div id="search-container"></div>
<div id="map" style="height: 500px;"></div>
```

A few key points to keep in mind:

- **Field masking matters for cost** — only request the fields you actually need in `fetchFields()`. You're billed per field category [Source 2].
- **`gmp-placeselect` replaces `place_changed`** — the legacy `Autocomplete` widget uses `place_changed`; the new element uses `gmp-placeselect` [Source 1].
- **The `Place` object is returned on the event** — unlike the legacy API, you don't call `getPlace()` on the widget; the place is directly on `event.place` [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Maps JavaScript API Overview](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/overview)

Loading the Maps JavaScript API in a React app requires some care to avoid SSR issues, map re-renders, and memory leaks. Here's the recommended approach using `@googlemaps/js-api-loader` with `useRef` and `useEffect`:

```javascript
import { useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import { Loader } from "@googlemaps/js-api-loader";

export default function MapComponent() {
  const mapRef = useRef(null);
  const mapInstanceRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Guard: only initialize once
    if (!mapRef.current || mapInstanceRef.current) return;

    const loader = new Loader({
      apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
      version: "weekly",
    });

    async function initMap() {
      const { Map } = await loader.importLibrary("maps");
      const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await loader.importLibrary("marker");

      mapInstanceRef.current = new Map(mapRef.current, {
        center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
        zoom: 12,
        mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID", // Required for AdvancedMarkerElement
      });

      // Example marker
      new AdvancedMarkerElement({
        map: mapInstanceRef.current,
        position: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
        title: "New York City",
      });
    }

    initMap();
  }, []);

  // Clean up event listeners if needed
  useEffect(() => {
    return () => {
      if (mapInstanceRef.current) {
        google.maps.event.clearInstanceListeners(mapInstanceRef.current);
      }
    };
  }, []);

  return <div ref={mapRef} style={{ width: "100%", height: "500px" }} />;
}
```

A few key points to keep in mind:

- **Use `useRef` for the map instance** — storing it in `useState` would cause unnecessary re-renders every time the map is set [Source 2].
- **Guard with `mapInstanceRef.current`** — prevents the map from being re-initialized on every render [Source 2].
- **Clean up event listeners** on unmount to avoid memory leaks [Source 2].

### If you're using Next.js

The Maps JavaScript API depends on `window`, which doesn't exist during server-side rendering. Wrap your map component with a dynamic import to disable SSR [Source 2]:

```javascript
// pages/index.js or app/page.js
import dynamic from "next/dynamic";

const MapComponent = dynamic(() => import("../components/MapComponent"), {
  ssr: false,
  loading: () => <div>Loading map...</div>,
});

export default function Page() {
  return <MapComponent />;
}
```

