## Directions API vs. Routes API

The core distinction is that the **Routes API is the modern, recommended replacement** for server-side routing, while the **legacy Directions API** continues to work but is no longer the preferred approach [Source 5]. For **client-side routing within the Maps JavaScript API**, `DirectionsService` and `DirectionsRenderer` remain the recommended approach regardless [Source 5].

### Key Improvements in the Routes API

The Routes API offers several advantages over the legacy Directions API [Source 5]:

- **Field masking** — You only request (and pay for) the specific fields you need
- **Better traffic modeling** — More accurate real-time traffic routing options
- **Polyline quality options** — Finer control over encoded route geometry
- **Toll information** — Built-in toll cost/road data
- **Two-wheeler routing** — Motorcycle/scooter support in select regions

### Routing Preferences (Routes API)

The Routes API introduces a tiered `routingPreference` system that also maps directly to billing SKUs [Source 1, Source 4]:

| Preference | Description | SKU Cost (per 1K) |
|---|---|---|
| `TRAFFIC_UNAWARE` | Fastest route, no traffic data | $5.00 (Basic) |
| `TRAFFIC_AWARE` | Considers current traffic | $10.00 (Advanced) |
| `TRAFFIC_AWARE_OPTIMAL` | Most accurate traffic routing | $15.00 (Preferred) |

### Routes API (REST) Example

```javascript
// Server-side: Routes API REST call
const response = await fetch(
  "https://routes.googleapis.com/directions/v2:computeRoutes",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      "X-Goog-Api-Key": "YOUR_API_KEY",
      // Field mask controls what's returned AND what you're billed for
      "X-Goog-FieldMask": "routes.duration,routes.distanceMeters,routes.polyline.encodedPolyline",
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      origin: { location: { latLng: { latitude: 40.7128, longitude: -74.0060 } } },
      destination: { location: { latLng: { latitude: 34.0522, longitude: -118.2437 } } },
      travelMode: "DRIVE",
      routingPreference: "TRAFFIC_AWARE",
    }),
  }
);
const data = await response.json();
```

### DirectionsService (Client-Side) Example

For displaying routes on a map, stick with `DirectionsService` [Source 1]:

```javascript
const directionsService = new google.maps.DirectionsService();
const directionsRenderer = new google.maps.DirectionsRenderer();
directionsRenderer.setMap(map);

directionsService.route(
  {
    origin: "New York, NY",
    destination: "Boston, MA",
    travelMode: google.maps.TravelMode.DRIVING,
    provideRouteAlternatives: true,
  },
  (result, status) => {
    if (status === google.maps.DirectionsStatus.OK) {
      directionsRenderer.setDirections(result);
      const leg = result.routes[0].legs[0];
      console.log(`Distance: ${leg.distance.text}`);
      console.log(`Duration: ${leg.duration.text}`);
    } else {
      console.error("Directions request failed:", status);
    }
  }
);
```

### Summary Recommendation

- **Building a server-side routing feature or Route Matrix?** → Use the **Routes API REST endpoint**.
- **Rendering routes on a web map?** → Use **`DirectionsService` + `DirectionsRenderer`** in the Maps JavaScript API.

