The `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` error means you've exceeded either your queries-per-second (QPS) or daily quota limit for a given API. This can happen with burst traffic or sustained high-volume usage [Source 2].

There are a few ways to resolve it:

1. **Implement exponential backoff** — retry failed requests with increasing delays
2. **Batch requests** where the API supports it
3. **Check your quota** in Cloud Console > APIs & Services > Quotas
4. **Request a quota increase** if your legitimate usage consistently hits the limit

Here's a robust retry implementation using exponential backoff [Source 2]:

```javascript
async function geocodeWithRetry(address, retries = 3) {
  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      const result = await geocoder.geocode({ address });
      return result;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error.code === "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT" && i < retries - 1) {
        // Wait 1s, then 2s, then 4s before each retry
        await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, Math.pow(2, i) * 1000));
        continue;
      }
      throw error; // Re-throw if out of retries or different error
    }
  }
}
```

If you're hitting quota limits regularly due to high traffic, also consider these cost/usage optimizations [Source 1]:

- **Use session tokens** with Places Autocomplete to avoid per-keystroke billing
- **Cache results** server-side (Google's ToS allows up to 30 days)
- **Set daily quota limits** in Cloud Console to prevent runaway usage — go to APIs & Services > Google Maps Platform > select the API > Quotas & System Limits

**Sources:**
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

Use the **Places API (New)** — specifically `PlaceAutocompleteElement` (the web component) or the `Autocomplete` class with the new `Place`-based patterns. The legacy `PlacesService` is being actively replaced, and the new API gives you meaningful advantages [Source 2, Source 3].

## Why the New API is Better

1. **Promise-based** — no more callback hell
2. **Field masking** — you only request and pay for the fields you need
3. **Session tokens** — easier to manage billing sessions correctly
4. **Better TypeScript support**
5. **`PlaceAutocompleteElement`** is a web component that handles UI for you

## Recommended Approach: `PlaceAutocompleteElement`

This is the newest and most recommended pattern [Source 1]:

```javascript
const placeAutocomplete = new google.maps.places.PlaceAutocompleteElement({
  componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
});

document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
  const place = event.place;
  await place.fetchFields({
    fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"],
  });
  console.log(place.displayName);
  console.log(place.formattedAddress);
});
```

## Alternative: `Autocomplete` Class (if you need more control)

If you need finer control over the input element [Source 2]:

```javascript
const { Autocomplete } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const autocomplete = new Autocomplete(
  document.getElementById("search-input"),
  {
    types: ["geocode", "establishment"],
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
    fields: ["place_id", "geometry", "formatted_address", "name"],
  }
);

autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", () => {
  const place = autocomplete.getPlace();
  if (!place.geometry) {
    console.error("No geometry returned for this place.");
    return;
  }
  map.setCenter(place.geometry.location);
  map.setZoom(15);
});
```

## Billing Note

Regardless of which new approach you use, make sure you're using **session tokens** to avoid being billed per-keystroke. Without them, each character a user types triggers a separately billed request [Source 5]:

```javascript
const sessionToken = new google.maps.places.AutocompleteSessionToken();

const service = new google.maps.places.AutocompleteService();
service.getPlacePredictions(
  { input: "pizza", sessionToken },
  (predictions) => { /* handle predictions */ }
);
```

Note: `PlaceAutocompleteElement` handles session tokens automatically — another reason to prefer it.

